oai_dc:dc.dc:title: CYLINDRICAL CAISSON BREAKWATER: STRAIN MODEL TESTS
oai_dc:dc.dc:creator: Gravesen, Helge
Brodersen, Finn P.
Larsen, Jorn S.
Lundgren, H.
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: model test
strain test
cylinder
caisson breakwater
breakwater design
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: The distribution of shook pressures on a vertical face breakwater is so random from one shock to the next that the determination of the internal forces in a thin-balled reinforced-concrete structure is difficult even when a large number of pressure cells is used in a model test. Therefore a technique has been developed that allows the direct determination of the internal stresses by means of strain gauges. The new technique has been applied to a breakwater consisting of a series of cylindrical caissons. The results show that a strain gauge model is more advantageous than a pressure cell model because of its simpler data analysis and better determination of the quantities required for design.
oai_dc:dc.dc:source: Coastal Engineering Proceedings; No. 15 (1976): Proceedings of 15th Conference on Coastal Engineering, Honolulu, Hawaii, 1976.; 137
